      "solution": "import java.util.*;\nclass Solution {\n  public static void main(String[] a){\n\n    Scanner in=new Scanner(System.in);\n\n    int n=in.nextInt(); \n  \n    int[] x=new int[n];\n\n    for(int i=0;i<n;i++) x[i]=in.nextInt();\n\n    int m=Integer.MIN_VALUE;\n\n    for(int i=0;i<n;i++) m=Math.max(m, x[i]+x[n-1-i]);\n\n    System.out.println(m);\n\n  }\n}",
      "statement": "You are given an integer [[N]] followed by a sequence of [[N]] integers.\nYour task is to find the <<largest mirrored sum>> — that is, the sum of two numbers that are at <<opposite ends>> of the sequence, i.e. the first with the last, the second with the second-to-last, and so on.\n\n<<Note>>: When [[N]] is odd, the middle integer is considered to be mirrored with itself.",
